<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,546,824]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,546,572]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Vertex with laterally flattened crest (
<figureCitation box="[693,837,546,572]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1717,1741]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-22@49.[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 27. Paraphidnia species. A–B. P. brevicristata. C–D. P. gallina. E–G. P. tunki. A, C, F. Head and pronotum in lateral view. B, D, G. Cerci in dorsal view. E. Habitus in lateral view." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs. 27C, F</figureCitation>
). Antennae nodose, scapus and sometimes pedicellus armed with a tubercle. Pronotum smooth and devoid of tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[891,1055,582,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1717,1741]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-22@49.[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 27. Paraphidnia species. A–B. P. brevicristata. C–D. P. gallina. E–G. P. tunki. A, C, F. Head and pronotum in lateral view. B, D, G. Cerci in dorsal view. E. Habitus in lateral view." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs. 27A,C,F</figureCitation>
). Sub-ocular region with cuticular evaginations. Wings projecting at an angle of 40–45 degrees upward. Ventral spines of middle tibia lamelliform. Abdominal tergites dorsally produced and with pointed tips (
<figureCitation box="[801,903,654,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1717,1741]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-22@49.[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 27. Paraphidnia species. A–B. P. brevicristata. C–D. P. gallina. E–G. P. tunki. A, C, F. Head and pronotum in lateral view. B, D, G. Cerci in dorsal view. E. Habitus in lateral view." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 27E</figureCitation>
). Male cerci with outer branch long and curved inward, inner branch of almost similar size or short and developed as small spiniform process (
<figureCitation box="[1237,1424,690,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1717,1741]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-22@49.[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 27. Paraphidnia species. A–B. P. brevicristata. C–D. P. gallina. E–G. P. tunki. A, C, F. Head and pronotum in lateral view. B, D, G. Cerci in dorsal view. E. Habitus in lateral view." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs. 27B, D, G</figureCitation>
). Basic coloration in life dark brown, with greenish and whitish spots.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1050,762,789]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="type_taxon">
