<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="key">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,530,1620,1683]" box="[151,518,1620,1647]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,518,1620,1647]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
Key to species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giglio-Tos" authorityYear="1898" box="[366,518,1620,1647]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Paraphidnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[366,518,1620,1647]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Paraphidnia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,530,1620,1683]" box="[151,530,1656,1683]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,530,1656,1683]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
(Cadena-Castañeda 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[395,444,1656,1683]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">et al</emphasis>
., 2016)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<key pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<keyStep pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,1726,1953]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<keyLead pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
1. Head round in frontal view, in lateral view eyes occupying dorsal half of head, crest little elevated, ocellar tubercle poorly developed (
<figureCitation box="[338,427,1755,1777]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1717,1741]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-22@49.[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 27. Paraphidnia species. A–B. P. brevicristata. C–D. P. gallina. E–G. P. tunki. A, C, F. Head and pronotum in lateral view. B, D, G. Cerci in dorsal view. E. Habitus in lateral view." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 27A</figureCitation>
)......................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Cadena-Castaneda &amp; Buzzetti, 2016" authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda &amp; Buzzetti" authorityYear="2016" box="[935,1436,1755,1777]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Paraphidnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicristata">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[935,1081,1755,1777]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">P. brevicristata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. &amp; Braun, H. &amp; Buzzetti, F. M." box="[1087,1436,1755,1777]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" pagination="15 - 23" refId="ref39616" refString="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J., Braun, H. &amp; Buzzetti, F. M. (2016 a) The tribe Dysoniini part V: The group Paraphidniae, with three new species from Guatemala and Ecuador (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Phaneropterinae). Journal of Orthoptera Research, 25 (1), 15 - 23. https: // doi. org / 10.1665 / 034.025.0104" type="journal article" year="2016">Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Buzzetti, 2016</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,1726,1953]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<keyLead pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
- Head higher than wide in frontal view, in lateral view eyes occupying more than half of the top of the head, crest and ocellar tubercle well developed (
<figureCitation box="[468,590,1814,1836]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1717,1741]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-22@49.[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 27. Paraphidnia species. A–B. P. brevicristata. C–D. P. gallina. E–G. P. tunki. A, C, F. Head and pronotum in lateral view. B, D, G. Cerci in dorsal view. E. Habitus in lateral view." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs. 27C, F</figureCitation>
).................................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,1726,1953]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<keyLead pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
2. Male cerci with small internal spine on the basal portion, distally of it tapering, bent inward, with almost straight distal portion (
<figureCitation box="[233,323,1872,1894]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1717,1741]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-22@49.[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 27. Paraphidnia species. A–B. P. brevicristata. C–D. P. gallina. E–G. P. tunki. A, C, F. Head and pronotum in lateral view. B, D, G. Cerci in dorsal view. E. Habitus in lateral view." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 27D</figureCitation>
)...................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Giglio-Tos, 1898" authorityName="Giglio-Tos" authorityYear="1898" box="[1174,1436,1872,1894]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Paraphidnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gallina">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1174,1266,1872,1894]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">P. gallina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Giglio-Tos, E." box="[1273,1436,1872,1894]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" pagination="1 - 108" refId="ref40510" refString="Giglio-Tos, E. (1898) Viaggio del Dr. Enrico Festa nella Republica dell'Ecuador et regioni vicine. VI. Ortotteri. Bollettino dei Musei di Zoologia ed Anatomia Comparata della R. Universita di Torino, 13 (311), 1 - 108." type="journal article" year="1898">Giglio-Tos, 1898</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,1726,1953]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<keyLead pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
- Male cerci bifurcate, outer part longer and uniformly curved inward, inner branch equally robust but shorter (
<figureCitation box="[1275,1365,1902,1924]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1717,1741]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-22@49.[151,1436,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 27. Paraphidnia species. A–B. P. brevicristata. C–D. P. gallina. E–G. P. tunki. A, C, F. Head and pronotum in lateral view. B, D, G. Cerci in dorsal view. E. Habitus in lateral view." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 27G</figureCitation>
)............................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Braun &amp; Buzzetti, 2016" authorityName="Braun &amp; Buzzetti" authorityYear="2016" box="[1125,1436,1931,1953]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Paraphidnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tunki">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1125,1201,1931,1953]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">P. tunki</emphasis>
Braun &amp; Buzzetti, 2016
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</key>
